## 31.10.2025 Family Dinneroo WBR \- Week 9

Author(s)/Contributor(s): [Abi Horner](mailto:abi.horner@deliveroo.co.uk) [Nico Phillpott](mailto:nicholas.phillpott@deliveroo.com.au)[Chloe Morgan](mailto:chloe.morgan@deliveroo.co.uk)[Johanne Soeun Chu](mailto:johanne.chu@deliveroo.com)[Iain Willmore](mailto:iain.willmore@deliveroo.co.uk)[Simon Jones](mailto:simon.jones@deliveroo.co.uk)[Chloe Hobson](mailto:chloe.hobson@deliveroo.co.uk)[James Barnes](mailto:james.barnes@deliveroo.co.uk)[Lina Gallego](mailto:lina.gallego@deliveroo.co.uk)[Leon Man](mailto:leon.man@deliveroo.co.uk)[Sheena Kotadia](mailto:sheena.kotadia@deliveroo.co.uk)[Anna Lawrence](mailto:anna.lawrence@deliveroo.co.uk)

***Follow up actions added to [8\. Follow-ups](#bookmark=id.fufzs0gocddw)***

### Summary (w/c 7.10.2025)

**Promising OV growth in W9 (+18% WoW), likely driven by:**

* Marketing \- improvements to paid social, CRM, and DXGY audiences all likely contributing factors to growing our awareness  
* Continued improvements across in-app visibility (additional pinning) and proposition (retagging) aiding conversion, despite some increased operational challenges

[***Proposition Performance:***](#bookmark=id.8jy7lqj4zkht) 

* We are now able to track total FTT and collection page sessions, users and conversion rates, alongside new-to-FTT vs returning-to-FTT cx *(albeit these are one week lagged, as we build scalability to make reporting self-serve)*  
  * Total FTT and collection page sessions are on an upward trajectory, while FTT session-to-conversion rates have shown consistent week-on-week increases, reflecting growing customer awareness, education, and consideration.  
  * Returning-to-FTT cx increased significantly during the first 7 weeks of the proposition, peaking at 36% in week 7, before slightly softening to 33%.  
* On broader proposition performance:  
  * There are positive signs of engagement, with share of orders from new-to-platform cx increasing (2% vs 1% last week) and more non-PLUS users beginning to use the proposition (65% PLUS vs 67% last week). Additionally, FTT cx are increasingly trying new brands (37% OV from new-to-brand cx vs 35% last week).  
  * However, ratings have declined for the 3rd consecutive week, dropping to 4.35 (vs 4.39 last week, 4.50 W7, 4.53 W6). Scheduled orders have also decreased to 17% (vs 18% last week and 20% W7 and W8), while family orders (per LBDS) declined to 16% (vs 17% last week).  
  * Top performing brands, cuisines and dishes \- alongside regional splits \- remain consistent.

[***Marketing:***](#bookmark=id.e47f0rcxdspk) 

**Media Insights:** We continue to be live across all channels with performance in line with expectations. In paid social our pacing has picked up and is now on track to deliver in full and recent optimisations have led to a significant positive update from our Brand Lift study.  We are currently working through (i) media upweight opportunities utilising ¬£200k DXGY underspend and (ii) H1 2026 plans. In w/c 17th we will use SteerCo for a more detailed mid-campaign deep dive into performance.

**DXGY:** Performance continues to pace behind business case assumptions, working with CRM and Product teams to drive improvement. Key Drivers: 9.5k have entered in total, with 369 Cx completing all steps. To date, ¬£9.1k vouchers have been earned, with spend at ¬£3.8k (vs total budget ¬£1m). Investigations concluded to identify and close gap in current wave; improve merchandising and upweight CRM with DXGY messaging; set up second wave of DXGY.

**CRM:** Launched Px selection email this week, with half term focus copy. Push continues to perform above benchmark, CTR (0.7% vs 0.6% benchmark), while conversion is performing above the average of previous weeks. In Nov, we will lead with GB messaging, and continue to explore opportunities to upweight or improve CRM.

[***Operations Performance***](#bookmark=id.xaawvvkuqgme) ***and [Care:](#bookmark=id.2bly6deyk5rk)*** 

**B10s:** 

* All key B10s have worsened WoW and continue to be elevated vs. Non-Dinneroo mealtimes. Unacceptable lates increased \+3.30 ppt WoW to 12.23%, RWT remaining stable at 9.8% (+2.6ppt WoW) both impacting OTP CPO) and OI increased \+0.55ppt WoW to 3.51%.  
* Our primary offenders across the three key B10 metrics continue to be: wagamama, Pho, and PEX, while we have seen marked improvements from Dishoom. These brands continue to be focused on in weekly Operating Theatre touchpoints.

**Care:**

* **Claims:** increased  vs prior week at 7.07% orders with a claim (+0.34 ppt WoW) and average claim amount at ¬£14.77 (+22p WoW), reflecting poorer operational performance, with Missing Items remaining the top offender for CCPO at 22p, while Unacceptable Lates also increased to 3.91%.  
* **OTP: 65p per Dinneroo order** (+18p WoW), which is **\+55p above [target](https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1VI8MI8jZlmiXNNKKB_cWaeiW9eH3rQ-LK4Gbrv_FJsw/edit)** (10p) and **\+44p above budget** (21p).  
* **1\* Rating Cx Strategy:** In Oct, \>200 Cx have left 1-star rating in response to FTT. Customers who did not receive OTP compensation have been contacted with ¬£25 credit and a note encouraging them to try Dinneroo again. Product team now have access to Zendesk to action this week without GE team assistance.

**UE Competing Proposition: It is worth flagging that Uber Eats have started approaching Px, inviting them to join a competing ‚ÄòFamily Meals \>¬£30‚Äô offering, not limited to cuisine or time-of-day, offering Cx free delivery. Slated to launch Nov/Dec, with marketing attached. More information on i) UE proposition and ii) our options to respond, to follow next week.**

### 1\. Proposition Performance

We can now track total FTT and collection page sessions**,** users and conversion rates on a daily basis. From next week, these metrics will be incorporated into the standard update, but for now they are highlighted at the top.

* **FTT sessions[^1], users and conversion** *(currently one week lagged, shifting to in-week reporting from next week; reported as Monday-Thursday only)*  
  * FTT sessions and session users show an upward trajectory. Growth from week 1 (wc 1/9) to week 5 (wc 29/9) was partly driven by the addition of new zones (via P2 onboarding). While there was a slight plateau between weeks 5 and 6, performance now appears to be trending upward again, potentially reflecting merchandising changes and lagged marketing effects, as no new zones have been unlocked since week 6\.   
  * Conversion rates are also on a consistent upward path, likely supported by growing consumer awareness and education, which encourage more intentional purchasing behaviour.

![][image1]![][image2]

* **Collection page sessions and users**  
  * Collection page sessions also show an upward trajectory. Growth between weeks 5 and 6 occurred despite total FTT sessions remaining flat. This may reflect that the reduction in merchandising activity during week 6 (carousel XP and Braze marketing pop-up stopped) negatively impacted overall FTT traffic, while increased marketing activity (i) encouraged more conversions from seeing Dinneroo merchandising and entering the collection and / or (ii) drove users directly to the collection page via CRM.

![][image3]

* **Returning-to-FTT Cx:** Returning-to-FTT cx has grown its share significantly since the launch of the proposition, as FTT continues to gain traction. Share increased consistently from week 1 (wc 1/9) to week 7 (13/10) where it peaked at 36% before softening to 34% in week 8 and 33% in week 9 (NB: week 9 data is only measured up to Wednesday and may change).

![][image4]

* **Order Composition**  
  * **Ordering patterns** \- scheduled orders down vs last week  
    * 17% scheduled (vs 18% last week, and 20% W6 & W7)  
  * **Top performing brands, cuisines, dishes** \- top brands, cuisines and dishes remain constant  
    * Top 5 brands: Pho, Wagamama, Dishoom, PEX, Banana Tree (same as last week)  
    * Top cuisines: Asian dominates (53% vs 53% last week), followed by Indian (15% vs 16% last week) and Italian (12% vs 12% last week)  
    * Top 3 dishes: Wags Family Chicken Katsu, Pho‚Äôs Pho the Whole Family and Dishoom‚Äôs Chicken Ruby (same as last week)  
* **Cx Composition \-** New-to-Roo and new-to-brand are up; at the same time, new-to-FTT has fallen. From a demographic POV, family split and location split remain similar.   
  * **New-to-Roo Cx:** 2% cx are new-to-platform (vs 1% last week)  
  * **New-to-Brand Cx:**  37% of orders are new to brand (vs 35% last week)  
  * **PLUS / Frequent Cx:** 65% of orders are from PLUS users (vs 67% last week); 60% return to platform (vs 61% last week)  
  * **Family split:** 16% Families per LBDS (vs 17% last week)  
  * **Location:** Similar to previous week: FTT OV composition by region closely aligns to total Roo GTV composition by region  
* **Cx Behaviour**  
  * **Ratings:** Down for the 3rd week in a row: 4.35 (vs 4.39 W8, 4.5 W7 and 4.53 W6); 1\* orders 8% (vs 8% last week), 72% 5\* (vs 73% last week)  
  * **Cx Funnel:** DS are currently scoping the process to productionise funnels, working with Analytics Engineering. This will surface the data in Looker.   
    * Funnels filtered to post marketing activity: [Family Dinneroo - Growing OV Oct-25](https://docs.google.com/presentation/d/1jmpXZ6y17sr5Lc2UvOKgQ7M6rNcUBI5zBynho-z9pbs/edit?slide=id.g39e7d886bb0_0_36#slide=id.g39e7d886bb0_0_36) Slides 7,9,11  
      * Overall, a similar story to what we saw with the entire date range  
        * Entrypoint \> View item: slight increases seen across entrypoints (vs platform)   
        * View item \> Add to basket: improved by roughly 8pp on home carousel (vs platform)  
      * DS Analysis of entry-point performance by zone suggests that traffic is the primary performance driver, rather than increased product selection. We did, however, find specific zones where boosting selection to the average level of high-performing zones could be beneficial. These zones are being prioritised in Site Expansion strategies.  
      * Next week, DS will deep dive into which Item Modals have a higher drop-out rate from Item view \> add to basket, to support the upcoming Family Dinneroo Home Merchandising Optimisation Product/SWE work.   
        * Other tasks in order of priority:  
          * Support with pulling a clearer view of sessions from Marketing sources.  
          * Unguided Performance \-using context from Marketing sources eg: X% sessions that don‚Äôt see an entry point land on the collection page.  
* **Brand Commentary \-** Zambrero have returned to the proposition after increasing portion sizes across all items (3 orders this week), while The Salad Project removed themselves, citing low order volume (avg, 10 orders/week) and concerns about their proposition vs competition. Commercial teams in conversation to bring them back online ASAP. 

### 2\. Marketing 

#### A) Media Insights ([Emily Lodge](mailto:emily.burke@deliveroo.co.uk)[Liz Wetz](mailto:liz.wetz@deliveroo.co.uk)[Russell Jackson-Pugh](mailto:russell.pugh@deliveroo.co.uk)) 

### 

* We continue to be live across all channels with our next burst of OOH activity going live from 3rd-16th November. Detailed performance by channel can be found here [Family Time Marketing Weekly Performance Update](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Epw1f4xddHHvC1jfIowJ_p3m-0-YAguc9MpMPowMc3I/edit?usp=sharing)  
* In paid social (discover pillar) our pacing has picked up and is now on track to deliver in full. Recent optimisations have led to a significant positive update from our Brand Lift study.  First measurement (6-19 Oct) results showed a promising \+3.37% increase in Ad Recall among the users who saw our ads (the test group) compared to the control group.   
* For digital audio, our ads are continuing to perform above benchmark (95%) on listen-through-rate by 3pts at an average of 97.9% across campaign lines to date, suggesting the audience we are reaching resonates with the ad. However postcode targeting continues to restrict impression and spend delivery. An optimisation we could consider is simplifying our asset mix (reducing from 2 assets to 1\) in this channel, as it‚Äôs currently split out due to Px variants of creative.  
* We have seen more micro-influencer affiliate content come through this week on our Metapic platform (16 unique influencers, 66 orders, ¬£2k OV) however this is still below our expectations so we are continuing to expand the network of creators we are going out to

Coming up/ other areas of investigation:

* From w/c 10th November the consumer insights team will be running a monthly Family Dinneroo pulse survey to 300 category users. The survey will look at unprompted awareness, prompted awareness & concept appeal.  
* We are investigating x2 proposed media upweight routes utilising the ¬£200k underspend from DXGY to drive further impact. We will share a more detailed proposal on these by Wednesday (5th)  
* We are continuing to work through our proposal for Family Time support in H1 2026  
* On 20th November in Steer Co we will provide a deepdive mid-campaign analysis alongside any proposals for further optimisations to the plan

**W/C 13th October \-** Search expanded their keyword remit to include Dish (e.g lasagna recipes), Brand (dinneroo), & additional generic terms (e.g cheap family meal recipes) to further increase reach. 

**W/C 20th October** \- As expected we still observe Generic related terms garner the majority of order volume, whilst Dish related terms showcase lower conversion rates. Branded terms were being cannibalised by BAU Brand \- these have been negated to ensure correct funneling of Dinneroo traffic to improve user journey. With the launch of wider awareness activity & keyword expansion, we have seen increased search volume & greater click traffic which is slowly scaling Search spend. 

#### C) DXGY Insights  ([Emma Wilson](mailto:emma.wilson@deliveroo.co.uk)[Sheena Kotadia](mailto:sheena.kotadia@deliveroo.co.uk)[Jordan Freedman](mailto:jordan.freedman@deliveroo.co.uk))

Performance continues to pace behind business case assumptions, working with CRM and Product teams to drive improvement. Key Drivers: 9.5k have entered in total, with 369 Cx completing all steps. To date, ¬£9.1k vouchers have been earned, with spend at ¬£3.8k (vs total budget ¬£1m).

**Progress since last week:**  
1\. 1\. Confirmed we‚Äôll redeploy underspends with ¬£200k into upweighting Family Dinneroo media, the remaining ¬£200k topping up NCs (to cover overspends and allow for ¬£15 off upweight in December)  
2\. Ireland campaign successfully re-launched Monday to xk Cx. This was following an error at launch where the audience table didn't fully populate therefore these Cx didn't go live.   
3\. Team planning to launch 2nd wave of DXGY for 10th Nov. The XP will be set up the same as Wave 1, removing Cx with a live DXGY.   
4\. Launched an additional CRM ‚ÄòLast chance‚Äô Push Notification to 1.1m Cx, with a 0.9% CTR (+0.1% above benchmark), generating 28 FT orders.  
5\. Funnel optimisations: 1\) DS have investigated the drop in entrants vs number of Cx ordered and identified that the issue affecting the Ireland audience above also affected 1k Cx in the UK. So of the 10k who had ordered, we had 7k entrants. The 3k difference is made up of 2k in the control group and 1k from this audience issue. The audience issue is now fixed, we expect no further Cx to be missing out as a result. 2\) Continuing to investigate with Product in app merchandising options to improve voucher usage, which has increased to 40% (versus the 85% benchmark), which is positive. 

**Next Steps:**

* Plan to open up more DXGY merch in December to Cx yet to place their first order (when GB is no longer live)

#### B) On-Time Promise 

This week‚Äôs gross OTP performance is **65p per Dinneroo order** (+18p WoW), which is **\+55p above [target](https://docs.google.com/document/u/0/d/1VI8MI8jZlmiXNNKKB_cWaeiW9eH3rQ-LK4Gbrv_FJsw/edit)** (10p) and **\+44p above budget** (21p). While we saw WoW improvements on Monday, daily performance worsened particularly on Wednesday, peaking at ¬£1.09 for daily OTP CPO, directly correlating to a 1.1ppt increase in Unacceptable Lates (15+ mins). 

We have investigated customer sentiment in relation to OTP, via CSAT responses:

* Within Agent CSAT more broadly, 25 CSAT responses were received with an aggregate score of 52%, with negative themes involving cold food, portion size and then lates.   
* Contacts largely are associated with ‚ÄòWhere is my order‚Äù or ‚ÄúOrder status query (not late)‚Äù typically comes from customers who perceive their order to be delayed when it‚Äôs still within the delivery window. Of these, CSAT responses are relatively low (\<10) and none were detractors. This indicates that when customers are engaging with our Agent Help relating to Lates, they are receiving positive help. 

With the help of Care DS, we are exploring two larger questions on the long-term impact of OTP, both of which are still being analysed:

1. *Is FTT OTP recovering bad order experiences?*   
2. *Is FTT OTP recovering bad order experiences to justify its cost?* 

To answer the second question, we are exploring either and XP or RDD (Regression Discontinuity Design) analysis, both of which are being scoped currently, but would require a lengthened period of time (\~12 weeks minimum) to be statistically significant given the low order volumes and use cases of OTP. Further updates will be provided in next week‚Äôs WBR.

#### C) 1-Star Rating Customer Strategy As we launched OTP in line with marketing on 6th October, and due to lack of GE team capacity, we paused our hypercare approach, meanwhile continuing Research‚Äôs survey outreach to customers, offering Amazon vouchers if they completed a survey about their experience (sent weekly). 

#### This week, we resumed a similar ‚Äòhypercare‚Äô strategy, targeting those customers who had i) left a 1-star review in the month of October, and ii) had not claimed OTP. We have excluded Order Help compensation, as we feel this strategy should be utilised to go ‚Äòabove and beyond‚Äô in attempting to win back customers. To ensure routine cadence, Product have gained access to Zendesk and had training from GE team, meaning we can manage and adjust the strategy without reliance on Care teams. 

#### To date, we have reached out to 181 eligible customers with ¬£25 credit and a note encouraging them to try Dinneroo again. We will update weekly with contacts, and usage of credit.

### 6\. Other Insights

#### A) Consumer Insights ([Simon Jones](mailto:simon.jones@deliveroo.co.uk), [Francesca McGovern](mailto:francesca.mcgovern@deliveroo.co.uk))

*Note: references to operational success are using the **perceived** and self-reported service quality as opposed to internal service metrics.*

**INSIGHTS SUMMARY:**

Families‚Äô hesitation is practical, not emotional: *‚ÄúWill this meal feed us all, arrive hot, and match the price I saw?‚Äù* 

**Overall performance perceptions**

* Operational reliability remains strong across the majority of partners. 85‚Äì95 % positive on on-time delivery, food condition, and packaging.  
* Family vs non-family experience is now aligned, confirming broad operational stabilisation while six partners remain under targeted Ops improvement.

**New insights this week**

* **Perceived value, not fulfillment, is now the growth barrier.** Families hesitate due to portion size credibility and unclear total pricing, not delivery or food quality. Families rate VFM 10‚Äì15 pp lower than non-families.  
* Habit Builders (Wagamama, Pho, Dishoom) show the strongest repeat behaviour (HBI \> 300), driving the majority of Dinneroo reorders.  
* Volume-Leakers such as itsu and Giggling Squid lose repeat customers despite reliable delivery; their menus under-signal value and flexibility.  
* Drop-off survey reconfirms the top three family barriers:  
  1. Not confident enough food for the price (13%)  
  2. Price higher than expected (11%)  
  3. Unclear portion information (9%)

**Next steps**

* Validate repeat behaviour further by applying LBDS segmentation to reordering data.   
* Confirm multi-session order conversion rate with Chloe‚Äôs analysis (over 50 % of drop-off respondents report returning to order later)

**Section 1: Order Experience & Operational Reliability**

*Data source: Consumer Feedback Survey sent out to all Dinneroo consumers who have opted-in to marketing (October Period, N \= 167, Families \= 92, Non-Family \= 75). Metrics coded as ‚ÄúYes/Agree/Strongly Agree‚Äù to service-quality questions (e.g. ‚ÄúDid your food arrive on time?‚Äù).* 

Service reliability is now a core strength across most partners. With fulfilment stabilised, we can focus on strengthening perceived value and trust signals alongside further operational fixes. 

Across every operational dimension, survey response satisfaction exceeds 85 percent. Differences between families and non-families are marginal (\< 3 percentage points), indicating reliable fulfilment across segments. This reflects steady improvements since launch and aligns with improving B10 service metrics.

*![][image6]*

**Section 2: Partner-Level Survey Insights.**

*Data source: Consumer Feedback Survey sent out to all Dinneroo consumers who have opted-in to marketing (October Period, N \= 167, Families \= 92, Non-Family \= 75). Questions: How did you feel about your meal? Why did you choose this dish? \[Value for Money\]*

**![][image7]** 

Partners that perform well on value **and** operational consistency are converting satisfaction into repeat orders.

* **Best in class:** *Pho*, *Wagamama*, and *Dishoom* deliver strong emotional satisfaction (90‚Äì96%) and consistent perceptions of value (54‚Äì63%).  
* **Middle tier:** *PizzaExpress* and *Banana Tree* perform reliably on satisfaction but do not differentiate on value.  
* **At risk:** *Bill‚Äôs* and *Giggling Squid* show a clear perception gap, similar operational results but lower value scores (\~42‚Äì49%).

Recent VFM survey evidence shows customers define ‚Äúworth it‚Äù through quality, speed, and freshness rather than price or offers.

This aligns directly with the partner-level data: those consistently delivering a faster, fresher, higher-quality meal are rated as better value and achieve higher reordering rates. Perceived value is determined by **how well the experience performs**, not necessarily by how it is priced. For underperforming partners, **improvements in portion clarity, consistency, and freshness cues may deliver the required uplift.** This alignment between perceived value and repeat behaviour is confirmed in the reordering data below.

Stickiness \= proportion of customers who reordered with the same partner. Inclusion: all Dinneroo partners. Period: rolling eight-week analysis aligned with the feedback window.*

**Habit Builders (Top 5\)**

* Combine scale and loyalty: average stickiness ‚âà 62 %.  
* Excel on **quality, freshness, and speed**. These partners maintain high customer satisfaction despite localised operational challenges noted by Px Ops.  
* Consistency and portion clarity underpin their high repeat rates.

**Niche Loyalists**

* Small but stable bases (\> 55 % stickiness).   
* Habit building within a brand, is lack of exploration across Dinneroo an issue?  
* Surfacing loyalists (Bill‚Äôs, Farmer J) may aid in building awareness of the wider proposition. 

**Volume Leakers & Underperformers**

* Stickiness below 55 % despite strong delivery reliability.  
* **Families rate VFM 10‚Äì15 pp lower than non-families in our consumer feedback survey. We hypothesise this is due to uncertainty about portion size and shareability.**  
* These partners should emphasise **portion guidance**, **family-size bundles**, **customisation** and **freshness or allergen info** in their menu copy.

*Note: Ops teams continue to address execution issues (spillages, packaging, portion calibration) across key partners. These improvements are expected to reinforce the strong reliability perception reflected in survey data.*

**Section 4: Drop-Off Survey & In-App Experience**

*Data Source: Drop-off Survey. Sample: All users who viewed Dinneroo but did not complete an order during the 30 minute analysis window. Metrics: Share of respondents selecting each reason (barriers) or potential improvement (motivators). Period: Continuous tracking, summarised over the past week.*

Operational reliability has improved across the board, but survey data shows that information gaps (not service issues) now hold families back from ordering. Families‚Äô hesitation is practical and information-based: *Will this meal feed us all, match the price I saw, and arrive hot?* Fixing those three questions through visible portion cues, upfront pricing, and reliability proof should be the immediate focus.

*![][image8]*

The latest drop-off survey shows the remaining friction points for families. The main deterrent is perceived value uncertainty: families in particular need reassurance on **portion size and price fairness**. Families tell us they would be most likely to oder when pricing and portions are explicit and the offering feels flexible.

*![][image9]*

|  | Opportunity | Supporting Data | Refinement |
| :---- | :---- | :---- | :---- |
|  | **1\. Portion Clarity** | 13 % cite ‚Äúnot enough food‚Äù \+ 9 % ‚Äúunclear portions‚Äù | Strengthen ‚ÄúFeeds 4‚Äù claims with weight or gram guidance, clear ‚Äúsuitable for X adults \+ Y children‚Äù tags, and distinguish between small and big-kid serving expectations. Encourage partners to include serving photos or tray-out shots that show quantity. |
|  | **2\. Transparent Pricing** | 11 % report price higher than expected |  |
|  | **3\. Variety & Customisation** | 28 % seek variety \+ 21 % want add-ons | Encourage bundles where each person gets their own dish type **or** where one main can be customised via add-ons included in delivery. |
|  | **4\. Reliability Proof** | 10 % want delivery assurance | Add reliability indicators (e.g. on-time X%, X% reordered, item-level reviews). Nico to confirm feasibility/timelines.  |
|  | **5\. Loyalty Nudge** | 19 % mention offers | Continue with DXGY rollout and monitor awareness.   |
